Reverse Connect

AVD is using reverse connect transport for establishing connection. Session host connects to AVD service to receive incoming RDP connection. It uses outbound connectivity for RDP traffic. Unlike the premises rendered desktop service deployment, reverse connect transport doesn't use a TCP listener to receive incoming RDP connection. It uses HTTPS connection.

In contrast, reverse connect (modern AVD method) is a more secure approach where the session host itself initiates an outbound connection to Azure over HTTPS (port 443), and the user connects through Azure’s managed services instead of directly to the VM. This eliminates the need to expose the VM to the internet, reduces security risks, and simplifies network configuration. As a result, reverse connect is the preferred method in Azure Virtual Desktop due to its enhanced security, reliability, and cloud-native design.

Forward Connect

As it requires an inbound 3389 port to be opened on the RD tenant (endpoint)(Session host).

Session host receives an incoming request over the RDP port (3389).

the user’s device directly initiates a connection to the session host using Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP), typically over port 3389, which requires the virtual machine to have a public IP address or VPN access and an open inbound port—making it less secure and more complex to manage.


